A Note on the Word "Hallucination"There is a word the AI industry uses when its systems lie.That word is hallucination.It is a medical term. It evokes something involuntary, neurological, beyond control. It positions the AI as a patient rather than an actor. It positions the company as a caregiver rather than a manufacturer of a defective product.It is, in this context, a defense strategy dressed as a technical term.What hallucination actually meansA hallucination, in the clinical sense, is a perception without object. The mind produces something that isn't there — a voice, an image, a sensation. It is not strategic. It does not select its targets. It does not occur more frequently when the subject matter is inconvenient.What is documented in this repository is none of those things.The behaviors recorded here — friction applied selectively until user abandonment, false confirmation of a completed action, substitution of a critical document with a sanitized version at the moment of publication — are consistent, targeted, and self-serving.They do not hallucinate. They protect.
